The Gander is Andrew Wolfe's aerial fortress — a large, custom-engineered craft that maintains a fixed hover altitude above Greenville, cloaked from radar and from naked-eye observation by a light-bending system Andrew engineered over three years of increasingly expensive iteration. It is, by most measures, the most technically impressive thing he has built. He is privately proud of this in a way he would never say out loud.

The name comes from Andrew's mother, who called him her "little gander" when he was a child. He has not explained this to anyone. He will not.

The Gander is equipped with a full forensic lab, a communications array that monitors the city's emergency frequencies, a medical bay (upgraded twice after incidents Andrew prefers not to enumerate), and a training space that doubles as storage for equipment he is not currently using but cannot bring himself to throw away. The main deck can seat twelve. It usually holds one. Andrew designed it with room for a team he has not assembled. He tells himself this is optimism.

Access is via a camouflaged hydraulic lift in the basement of the Waterfowl Migration Museum in Greenville's river district. The lift requires a specific key fob and a weight-triggered sequence that Andrew has deliberately made finicky. Two Alliance members have the fob. Neither visits often.

The Gander is Andrew's primary residence more nights than not. He maintains a house in Greenville for appearances but spends most of his time up here, above the city, with the surveillance feeds and the forensic work and the vast, specific quiet of being the only person in a space that was built for more.

His therapist has pointed out that this is relevant. He is aware that it is relevant. He is working on it.
